snippet.textDisplay:
Literally the only important differences between this van and the '95 Pontiac Transport van my father had in the '90s is the power sliding door, leather seats, and the 3.4L engine. (ours had the 3.1L - and yes it was as slow as you'd imagine)
Otherwise - it's literally the exact same vehicle - the controls, climate system controls, radio, wiper and headlight switches, seats (minus the built in child seat) - EVERYTHING - was shared between the two vehicles - I'd never even know this was a different vehicle by only looking at the interior. It could literally pass for an upgraded trim of the Transport if someone slapped a Pontiac logo on the front.
snippet.textOriginal:

snippet.textDisplay: I had a 91 Lumina van (same body) in high school. it was black interior and exterior. it had many names in school. such as the door wedge, the tie fighter, the dust buster, the cheese wedge, you get it. It had a 3.1L engine and you could roll back burnout the hell out of it. I took the back seats out of it and added 3 boat batteries, 3 amps and 6 subs. the rear hatch got stuck shut from the vibrations and then the side door. my parents got tired of buying front tires and hearing my bass. so then I received a 94 Saturn SL not a 1 or a 2 no just SL the slowest car ever. It couldn't even spin tires on wet blacktop. it had a power sunroof. that was the only power thing it had. so I traded it for a 94 cavalier coupe. the backseat in that car was for backpacks only. otherwise you had to sit sideways in it. but it was cool looking at the time and often got mistaken for a fox body at night. I ended up put an air dam on the front and a nice stereo. it was aqua color which was cool for its time. kept that car until 2017.

snippet.textDisplay:
Yes it was ugly and people made fun of it. But if you had three small kids under three like we did, the bright red Pontiac Trans Sport (with the updated front end) equipped with a smooth running 3800 V6 that I bought new for my wife was a welcome family hauler. We traveled in comfort, it had sufficient power to get on highways, and it got decent gas mileage. A vehicle that I thought was a joke at first sight became dear to me very quickly once I got behind the wheel.


This is a nice survivor.

snippet.textDisplay:
Let me give you a little story.
My parents bought their first minivan in 1990 it was a Dodge Caravan. It was a pile of shit we had it for about 75,000 miles we lost seven transmissions had it overheat twice within the first year and had numerous recalls. Then my parents bought a 1994 owes Mobile silhouette identical to what you have above except it was a dark green. That was by far the best vehicle we’ve ever owned it was 100,000 miles when my parents got rid of it and it was 100% mechanically sound. It was very reliable but I totally agree with you it’s very odd not to see them around today because we had such good luck with ours. I really liked the idea of the fiber glass or plastic panels because they would not rust out or show dings and dents. The only downfall I did not like about the van was that long front end and a dashboard you could pretty much sleep two people on. So learning your distances was very tough in the front. We drove it up here in Pittsburgh Pennsylvania through all the winters and believe it or not it ran well with studded snow tires I believe the balance was set up perfect for the weight distribution over the front end.
